---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "YMAX Dividend Analysis & History",
  description: "Explore the current YMAX dividend yield, payout schedule, and five-year history. Could this high-yield strategy be the cornerstone of your income portfolio?",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "YMAX Dividend Analysis & History",
    "description": meta.description,
    "datePublished": meta.published,
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the ymax dividend yield?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The current dividend yield for YMAX is approximately 82.07%. Because this is an actively managed derivative income fund, the yield can fluctuate significantly based on options premiums and market volatility."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How often does ymax pay a dividend?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "YMAX typically pays distributions on a monthly basis, providing a regular income stream for investors."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the ymax dividend history?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "YMAX has paid significant distributions since its inception. For example, in 2024 total payouts were $7.49 per share, and in 2025 they rose to $7.85 per share."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is the ymax dividend safe?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "YMAX generates income by selling options on other YieldMax ETFs. The dividend is not guaranteed and depends entirely on the premiums generated by its active options strategy, meaning the payout amount will vary."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does ymax generate its dividend?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "YMAX is a 'fund of funds' that invests in other YieldMax ETFs, which themselves employ covered call strategies on individual stocks to generate high monthly income."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/ymax-dividend-history" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>YMAX Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Comprehensive data on YieldMax Universe Fund of Option ETFs</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>YMAX Overview & Key Metrics</h2>
      <p>The <strong>YieldMax Universe Fund of Option ETFs (YMAX)</strong> is an actively managed fund designed for aggressive income investors. Operating as a "fund of funds," YMAX allocates its capital across various other YieldMax ETFs. These underlying funds utilize covered call options strategies on single stocks to generate extraordinarily high yields.</p>

      <p>Because the distributions are derived from options premiums rather than traditional corporate cash flows, the payouts can vary widely from month to month depending on market volatility. This strategy captures the upside premium from volatile tech and consumer stocks while seeking to distribute that cash flow to shareholders.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Current Snapshot</h3>
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th>Current Dividend Yield</th>
              <td>82.07%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Assets Under Management (AUM)</th>
              <td>$446.96 Million</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Category</th>
              <td>Derivative Income</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Payout Frequency</th>
              <td>Monthly</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>Investors must note that yields exceeding 80% are inherently linked to capital depreciation in flat or down markets. The total return of YMAX includes both these massive distributions and the price action of the underlying ETFs, which frequently experience NAV decay over time.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>YMAX Dividend History</h2>
      <p>Tracking the <strong>ymax dividend history</strong> reveals the aggressive nature of the fund's payout profile. Since its recent inception, the fund has maintained a monthly distribution schedule, though the absolute amount of cash paid out each month fluctuates based on the volatility of the underlying individual stocks.</p>

      <p>Below is a summary of the total annual payouts based on historical data:</p>

      <div class="card">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Total Annual Payout (per share)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>2024</td>
              <td>$7.49</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2025</td>
              <td>$7.85</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2026 (YTD)</td>
              <td>$0.81</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>Recent monthly payouts in early 2026 have ranged between $0.07 and $0.08 per share. While the <strong>ymax dividend</strong> amounts appear highly lucrative, it is critical to compare the distributions against the fund's share price to understand the true total return. The high <strong>ymax dividend yield</strong> is a hallmark of the YieldMax product suite.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Dividend Reinvestment (DRIP) Calculator</h2>
      <p>Reinvesting distributions—especially at yields near 82%—can result in rapid share accumulation. However, due to the NAV decay typical of covered call strategies, modeling a simple DRIP without accounting for principal erosion can be misleading. Use the calculator below to estimate your 12-month forward income based on the current yield, assuming the yield remains constant and the distributions are reinvested.</p>

      <div class="card calculator-container">
        <h3>Project Your YMAX Income</h3>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="sharesInput" style="display:block; margin-bottom:0.5rem; font-weight:bold;">Shares Owned:</label>
          <input type="number" id="sharesInput" value="100" min="1" style="width:100%; padding:0.75rem; border-radius:6px; border:1px solid var(--border-color); background:var(--bg-color); color:var(--text-primary);">
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="priceInput" style="display:block; margin-bottom:0.5rem; font-weight:bold;">Current Price per Share ($):</label>
          <input type="number" id="priceInput" value="15.00" step="0.01" style="width:100%; padding:0.75rem; border-radius:6px; border:1px solid var(--border-color); background:var(--bg-color); color:var(--text-primary);">
        </div>
        <button id="calcBtn" style="background:var(--accent-color); color:#fff; border:none; padding:0.75rem 1.5rem; border-radius:6px; font-weight:bold; cursor:pointer; width:100%;">Calculate Annual Income</button>

        <div id="calcResults" style="margin-top: 1.5rem; display:none; padding:1rem; background:var(--bg-color); border-radius:6px; border:1px solid var(--border-color);">
          <p style="margin:0 0 0.5rem 0;">Estimated Annual Income (No Reinvestment): <strong id="resNoDrip" style="color:var(--accent-color); font-size:1.2rem;">$0.00</strong></p>
          <p style="margin:0;">Estimated Annual Income (With DRIP): <strong id="resDrip" style="color:var(--accent-color); font-size:1.2rem;">$0.00</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem; color:var(--text-secondary); margin-top:0.5rem;">*Assumes a static 82.07% yield and constant share price. In reality, derivative income yields and NAV fluctuate significantly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Comparison to Category Average</h2>
      <p>When evaluating YMAX against the broader Derivative Income category, the contrast is stark. Traditional covered call ETFs, such as those tracking the S&P 500 (like <a href="/spyi-dividend-history">SPYI</a>) or the Nasdaq 100, typically yield between 8% and 12%. YMAX's yield of over 80% places it in an extreme tier of risk and reward.</p>

      <p>The category average for derivative income funds focuses on capital preservation combined with enhanced yield. YMAX, conversely, sacrifices capital preservation entirely in pursuit of maximum monthly cash flow. Investors must determine if this aggressive posture aligns with their overall portfolio strategy.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the ymax dividend yield?</summary>
        <p>The current dividend yield for YMAX is approximately 82.07%. Because this is an actively managed derivative income fund, the yield can fluctuate significantly based on options premiums and market volatility.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How often does ymax pay a dividend?</summary>
        <p>YMAX typically pays distributions on a monthly basis, providing a regular income stream for investors.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the ymax dividend history?</summary>
        <p>YMAX has paid significant distributions since its inception. For example, in 2024 total payouts were $7.49 per share, and in 2025 they rose to $7.85 per share.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is the ymax dividend safe?</summary>
        <p>YMAX generates income by selling options on other YieldMax ETFs. The dividend is not guaranteed and depends entirely on the premiums generated by its active options strategy, meaning the payout amount will vary.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does ymax generate its dividend?</summary>
        <p>YMAX is a 'fund of funds' that invests in other YieldMax ETFs, which themselves employ covered call strategies on individual stocks to generate high monthly income.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const calcBtn = document.getElementById('calcBtn');
      if(calcBtn) {
        calcBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const shares = parseFloat(document.getElementById('sharesInput').value) || 0;
          const price = parseFloat(document.getElementById('priceInput').value) || 0;
          const yieldPct = 0.8207; // 82.07%

          const principal = shares * price;
          const incomeNoDrip = principal * yieldPct;

          // Simple monthly compounding approximation for DRIP
          const monthlyRate = yieldPct / 12;
          const finalValue = principal * Math.pow(1 + monthlyRate, 12);
          const incomeDrip = finalValue - principal;

          document.getElementById('resNoDrip').textContent = '$' + incomeNoDrip.toLocaleString(undefined, {minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2});
          document.getElementById('resDrip').textContent = '$' + incomeDrip.toLocaleString(undefined, {minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2});
          document.getElementById('calcResults').style.display = 'block';
        });
      }
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    /* NO :root block. Use CSS vars: --bg-color, --card-bg, --border-color, --accent-color, --text-primary, --text-secondary */
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    th, td { padding: 0.75rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
    .calculator-container label { color: var(--text-primary); }
    a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; }
    a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
